## ✨ Features

- **🚀 Asynchronous Processing** - Non-blocking AT command execution
- **📚 Modular Architecture** - Ready-to-use TCP, SMS, GPRS implementations
- **⚡ Efficient Memory Usage** - Built-in TLSF memory allocator
- **🔒 Thread Safety** - Critical sections for RTOS environments
- **🛡️ Reliability** - DBC (Design by Contract) system integration
- **🔧 Flexible Configuration** - Customizable timeouts, retries, execution flow
- **📊 Advanced Debugging** - Detailed process logging
- **🔄 Ring Buffer Support** - Efficient data handling

## 📟 Supported Modems

- SIM800 series (SIM800L, SIM800C, SIM800H)
- SIM7000 series (SIM7000G, SIM7000E, SIM7000C)
- SIM7600 series (SIM7600G-H, SIM7600CE)
- SIM900 series
- Other SIMCom modules with AT command interface

## 🚀 Quick Start

### 1. Installation

Add these files to your project:
```
atl_library/
├── atl_core.[ch]           # Core library
├── atl_mdl_general.[ch]    # Basic modem functions
├── atl_mdl_tcp.[ch]        # TCP/IP connections
├── atl_mdl_sms.[ch]        # SMS handling
├── ringslice.[ch]          # Ring buffer utilities
├── tlsf.[ch]              # Memory allocator
└── dbc_assert.h           # Contract system
```

### 2. Basic Setup

```c
#include "atl_core.h"

// Your buffers and variables
static uint8_t rx_buffer[1024];
static uint16_t ring_head = 0, ring_head = 0;

// UART functions
void my_printf(const char* format, ...) {
    // Your printf implementation
}

uint16_t my_uart_write(uint8_t* data, uint16_t len) {
    // Your UART write implementation
    return len;
}

// Initialize ATL library
atl_init(my_printf, my_uart_write, rx_buffer, 
         sizeof(rx_buffer), &ring_tail, &ring_head);
```

### 3. Basic Usage

```c
// Callback for operation completion
static void modem_init_cb(bool success) {
    if (success) {
        printf("Modem initialized successfully!\n");
    } else {
        printf("Modem initialization failed!\n");
    }
}

// Initialize modem
atl_mdl_modem_init(modem_init_cb);

// Main processing loop
void main_loop(void) {
    while (1) {
        atl_entity_proc();
        // Your other application logic
    }
}
```

